net.java.jddac.jmci.units
Class ScaleType

java.lang.Object
  net.java.jddac.jmci.units.ScaleType

public final class ScaleType
extends java.lang.Object

The ScaleType of a unit describes how the unit maps from physical quantities to human-readable (and computer-storable) representations. The mapping to numbers, for example, can be linear, logarithmic, or increasing but with no other relationship, e.g. the Mohs hardness scale or the Richter scale. There can be mappings to non-numbers, such as to true/false, or "small"/"medium"/"large". There can be mappings to mixed numbers and non-numbers, such as to "08:45:15.02 June 6, 1998". There is no universally-accepted set of scale types. The set here omits scales which run arithmetically backwards (e.g. golf scores), geometrically backwards (e.g. pineapple sizes, which record the number that fit in a standard box), and doubtless others. There is also no agreement on the names of the types.

The javax.units package makes no use of any types but RATIO, LOG and OFFSET. The others are included as a possible aid to overlying packages. These are in order of decreasing mathematical well-behavedness, and have disjoint bit patterns. Implementations can depend upon this, for constructing tables, switch statements, etc. The initial work was Stevens, S. S. "On the theory of scales of measurement," Science, 103, pp677-680, 1946. A more modern, readable and relevant treatment appears in Fenton and Pfleeger, "Software Metrics -- A Rigorous and Practical Approach," PWS Publishing, 1997. In the field descriptions below, let m(x) be the "measure" of x -- the number (or whatever) that the unit maps the magnitude of a physical phenomenon to, where x is that magnitude.

Constant Field Values

RATIO

public static final int RATIO
A unit with RATIO scale type reports reports a number proportional to the magnitude of a quantity. It is so-called because it preserves the ratio property of measurements: m(x)/m(y) = x/y.

See Also:

LOG

public static final int LOG
A unit with LOG scale type reports reports the logarithm of the ratio of two magnitudes (or a single magnitude, even though this is mathematically a no-no -- see pH). m(x)-m(y) = k(x/y).

See Also:
Constant Field Values

OFFSET

public static final int OFFSET
A unit with OFFSET scale type reports a number offset from a number which is proportional to the magnitude of a quantity. Celsius is a common example. These units often report the distance to some origin in whatever space the unit is associated with. Thus, house numbers and Julian dates are also examples. m(x)-m(y) = k(x-y).

See Also:
Constant Field Values

ORDINAL

public static final int ORDINAL
A unit with ORDINAL scale type reports a number which preserves relational operations, but nothing stronger. m(x)>m(y) iff x>y; and similarly for =, <, etc.

See Also:
Constant Field Values

NOMINAL

public static final int NOMINAL
A unit with NOMINAL scale type maps quantities onto numbers (or non-numbers) which serve only as identifiers. There is no assumption of order, let alone mathematical relationship, in the mapped values. Examples are the numbers on players' jerseys. Since no ordering is implied, the domain need not be magnitudes (e.g. boolean truth, day of the week), and the range need not be numeric (e.g. "green"/"red"/"blue"). m(x)=m(y) iff x=y.

See Also:
Constant Field Values

public static final int ARBITRARY
If a unit has ARBITRARY scale type, we make no claims at all about the relationship between it and the associated quantity.
